<HEADLINE>
<P>
QANTAS RAIDS HONG KONG'S POOL OF TALENT; 
</P>
<P>
OFFERS PASSPORTS TO MAINTENANCE WORKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Financial Times of London 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Australian airline, Qantas, is attempting to recruit maintenance and 
engineering staff from the Hong Kong airport by offering them jobs that will 
ultimately entitle them to Australian passports. Nearly a third of the staff 
are seriously considering the offer. 
</P>
<P>
The move, a coup for Qantas, which is desperately short of skilled engineers 
and maintenance staff, will be a further blow to confidence in Hong Kong, which 
is suffering an accelerating brain drain as its best qualified people leave in 
search of security and passports elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong government and Cathay Pacific, the colony's airline, are 
understood to have expressed concern to the Australian government in Canberra. 
Hong Kong officials also raised the issue with Sir Geoffrey Howe, the British 
foreign secretary, during his visit last week, citing it as a dramatic example 
of the crippling effect the brain drain will have on the local economy if the 
right of abode in the United Kingdom is not granted to Hong Kong people. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Many May Accept 
</P>
<P>
Qantas, which is also trying to recruit in Singapore, Britain and Ireland, sent 
airline executives to Hong Kong together with an Australian immigration 
official. 
</P>
<P>
The airline interviewed more than 150 of the 400 engineering employees of 
Haeco, which provides maintenance services to airlines operating in and out of 
Hong Kong's Kai Tak international airport. Up to 130 are expected to join 
Qantas and move to Australia within two to six months, once applicants produce 
professional and technical certificates and immigration documentation. 
</P>
<P>
The loss of more than 100 licensed engineers at Haeco would deal a severe blow 
to the company. The Hong Kong government and Cathay Pacific would like the 
departures staggered over a longer period to allow Haeco time to adjust. About 
50% of Haeco's business comes from Cathay Pacific Airways, which like Haeco, is 
part of the Swire group of companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
QANTAS AIRWAYS LTD; EMPLOYEE RECRUITING; HONG KONG -- EMIGRATION; AIRPORTS -- 
HONG KONG; AUSTRALIA -- IMMIGRATION; CATHAY PACIFIC AIRWAYS LTD; HONG KONG -- 
GOVERNMENT; AIRLINE WORKERS -- EMPLOYMENT 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
